<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT/DTA-466 Diesel Engine Service (1990) - CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND SLEEVES - CYLINDER SLEEVE
        REMOVAL - CLEANING
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="2">
        <title>CLEANING</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Connecting Rod, Piston &#38; Rings</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean the aluminum pistons using a soap and water solution; soak, then clean, using a
                    non-metallic brush.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Never use a caustic solution or a wire brush for cleaning the aluminum pistons.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">All piston ring grooves must be cleaned thoroughly. Be sure the two drilled or cast oil
                    holes in the oil ring groove are open.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The following disassembled components may be cleaned using a suitable solvent:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Piston rings</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Piston pins</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Piston pin retainers</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Connecting rods</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Connecting rod caps</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Connecting rod bolts</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean all rod bolt hole and threads thoroughly.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean the oil hole at the top of the rod. Make sure it is not blocked.
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150612">Remove Piston Pin.</hotlnk>
                </para>
                <figure id="ef4150612" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11560" filename="../figcg1/CG11560.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.12. Remove Piston Pin.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150613" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11561" filename="../figcg1/CG11561.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.13. Remove Piston Rings.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Cylinder Sleeves</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Soak the cylinder sleeves in a soap and water solution and clean thoroughly using a
                    non-metallic brush.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Dry with filtered compressed air.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
